<h1>Yes!!!  These are Nagafen Underoos!!!</h1>
<B>I still have yet to understand why the /inspect on/off was added to the game.  This was supposed to keep people from accidently inspecting you when they target you.<P>I would of preferred to see the /inspect on/off make it so others cannot inspect me.<P>I find it rather annoying having players just run up and inpect me 10-20 times to get my attention or just be an irritant.  <P>If someone wants to see what I am wearing then they should be polite enough to ask if they may inspect me and at that point I can turn my /inpect on to allow it.<P>And yes, when you inspect me... you will see my message about how self concious I am about whether you can see my britches...<P>Bolerro<BR>18th Season Druid<BR>Vazaelle</B><P>Let me go over the philosophy of 'inspection'.  The first thing to keep in mind is that nobody is actually inspecting you, at least not in the way that the word would indicate.  They are looking at you closely, not turning your clothing inside out to see the labels.<P>Inspection does not show your britches.<P>What it does show are the things that the game engine doesn't show.  If your character is wearing a cloak the only way to know it is to 'inspect' them.  The game engine isn't showing what would otherwise be obvious.  Inspection only shows the name of an item and it's type (and only that by the icon that shows in inventory).  Inspection does not reveal what is in a bag, stats on any item, or what color underwear your character has on.  It only shows enough information to allow other players to know what your character would actually look like if the game engine could show every item you are wearing.<P>There is nothing invasive about inspecting someone.<P>Now if the messages that you receive from the game about someone 'inspecting' you are bothersome, you can turn those off.  That would prevent people from using inspection to annoy you.<P>I don't disagree with the idea that it is polite to ask someone before you inspect them.  But, like many courtesies, it certainly is not necessary.  You have the tools you need at your disposal to remove the factor that irritates you about it, should you choose to use them.<P>Alan<BR>

<hr>

Saeul wrote:<P><B>I think this is an important discussion and it traces all the way back probably to Isle of Kesmail and certainly to Dragon's Gate and Gemstone.  In a PvP environment, inspection often leads to an attack if you can loot what you inspected.<P>In a non-PvP environment, the only britches being shown are the knickers of the inspectee getting in a wad if they complain.  Probably it is viewed by most people as the only version of 'personal space' and that is why people often demonstrate upsetness at being inspected.  (Personal space being [in western societies] approximately an 18 inch radius cylinder around the surface of your body.)<P>BUT, an inspection is really what you say it is:  just a mechanism for people to actually know what someone is wearing.  People really are being silly when they treat it as something else other than that.  I would not even make it a matter of politeness AND it wouldn't matter at all if the game did not offer a message when someone else 'inspects' you.<P>Perhaps the game designers could elaborate on why that message exists to put the user community at rest?  And if the reason isn't a good one, just take the silly feature out of the game so no one ever knows when someone else is looking at them??</B><P>Actually, the idea to remove the message came up.  But it has its uses in the PvP environment.  And some people like to know when they are being looked at closely by others (in much the same way that I might squint to get a better look at the logo on your shirt).  There really is no need to remove it, we just went for the more flexible idea, allow players to choose to turn it off if they wish.<P><BR>Rokke_MT wrote:<P><B>I don't think you have been in a newbie area or city lately.  Running my higher level characters, I almost always switch to Anonymous whenever I go into one of these zones to stop the begging.  In fact this has become a very common thing for many of the players I know.  However, lately the "Beggars" have simply taken to inspecting...and judging who to annoy by equipment.  <P>This is truly harassment. I will get as many as 10-12 tells when I go into some of the cities like Kelethin and Freeport (not to speak of Riverview).  Many of these tells are followed by more of the "Please, please, Please Gimme Gimme Gimme" variety.  <P>Please change this so we can go to the bank in peace.  I hate being rude to people but after a few minutes of this, I am beginning to get a serious attitude - and judging from the common OOC's I see, I am certainly not alone.</B><P>That sort of 'harassment' is unrelated to their ability to inspect you.  If you have shiny armor on or if you're carrying a glowing sword, those people will still beg off you.  The fact that they are inspecting you first has very little to do with whether or not they beg.<P>They best solution if you are really in need of a respite would be to bag up your fancy stuff before you get to town.  They can see it visually, the inspection only happens after they see that you have something cool on.<P><BR>Noreya wrote:<P><B>Although on most of servers I'd agree with you, but I have one question. When was the last time you played on a PvP server? Being inspected is not only evasive, it can be a death sentence! Besides, if I'm wearing a robe or a cloak.. how is anyone supposed to see UNDER IT to know what Im wearing? I understand if the technical aspects of reworking this part of the game prohibit the changes, but please don't belittle this. The vast majority of people I have spoken to feel that being inspected is rude and undesirable... as roleplayer, my primary character certainly would not allow anyone to inspect what items I have without asking.</B><P>I most certainly understand the emotional issues.  I understand that there is no way that I can 'convince' you that your emotional reaction is wrong.  In fact, I don't believe that your emotional reaction is 'wrong' at all.  It's how you feel.  But, by the same token, you can't convince me (or the others that agree with me) that my feelings on this matter are wrong either.  Hence the impasse.<P>Neither viewpoint is right or wrong from an emotional stance.  So we can't rely on emotional reactions, we have to use logic.  And if you look at the strict game mechanics without allowing emotion to become a factor, I think the answer has to be to allow inspection exactly as it stands now.<P>I wanted to also touch on the PvP thing.  Again, I see inspection as a good thing in PvP.  I picture an old west bar scene, where one fellow eyes the other just the wrong way...<P>"What er you lookin at!"<P>That sort of thing.<P>As long as you avoid the emotional response that leads you to think of inspection as a violation of personal space, the solution seems clear to me.<P>But I've been wrong before...<P>Alan<BR>

<hr>

<B>You wrote:<P>&gt; There is nothing invasive about inspecting someone.<P>I disagree. Most people I encounter say 'sorry' if they inspecet me by accident. I do the same. It is a socially unacceptable practice to inspect without asking, because it is felt to be invasisve. You should take the (maybe unwritten) social rules into account, not just the fact that the game engine cannot show all equipment I am wearing.<P>Gorit, <BR>Erollisi Marr</B><P>And I do.  But just because something has somehow become a social rule doesn't mean that there should be a change to the game software.<P>All I can do is point out the logical (as I see it) reason why the game works the way it does.  I certainly can't enforce or belittle the social ethics of players that play within the game rules.  I also ask for forgiveness when I accidentally inspect someone.  But I don't do it because I find inspection offensive, I do it because some people do find it offensive and because it seems like the polite thing to do when you don't know how that person feels about it.<P><BR>I normally don't break into a message, but this one was long enough that I think my responses will make more sense if I put them right under the text that I'm responding to.  My comments are the ones that are not in bold.<P><B>Alan,<P>You stated "I most certainly understand the emotional issues. I understand that there is no way that I can 'convince' you that your emotional  reaction is wrong. In fact, I don't believe that your emotional reaction is 'wrong' at all. It's how you feel. But, by the same token,  you can't convince me (or the others that agree with me) that my feelings on this matter are wrong either. Hence the impasse."<P>I would like to attempt to convince you otherwise.</B><P>Go for it.<P><B>First, because the fact that some people ARE offended at being inspected, it already lends credibility to that fact that it is offensive. Example:  If I say you are an arse, you may or may not be offended.. but the fact is, since I KNOW you MAY be offended, and I said it anyway,   I was being offensive.  If you inspect me without asking, I may or may not be offended... but that fact is, since you KNEW I MAY  be offended, and you inspected anyway, you were being offensive.  That is the crux of my argument.  If it is common KNOWLEDGE that behavior MAY be offensive, to do so is in fact acting offensively.  Surely it is a matter of common courtesy.</B><P>Fair enough.  And I generally do not inspect people for that very reason.  However, even in real life I rarely put effort into attempting to avoid other people's 'irrational' concerns.  I'm NOT suggesting that this is the case here.  But let's look at your example.  It is far more likely that calling someone an arse will be offensive than, say, calling them a funny person.  The reasons for that are partially cultural and partially due to intent.<P>'Arse' is generally considered an impolite thing to call people.  That's the cultural thing, and that's something that, as an individual, I can't do much to change.  But the word has meaning above and beyond it's use as a potential insult.  Using that word means something impolite, so calling someone an arse is, almost by definition, rude.<P>But the term 'funny person' could have two meanings (or more, I suppose).  Depending on the people you are talking to, it could be offensive.  But the rest of what it implies would be almost entirely contextual.  If someone had just told a joke and if the speaker did not use a sarcastic tone, then it would be a compliment for most people.  If it was used when the person was trying to be serious or with enough sarcasm in the voice, it would most likely be an insult.<P>The word 'funny' itself isn't a bad word.  So it's not going to be something that we would police in game, for example.  No need to remove the word from the vocabulary because it might offend someone.<P>I hope that wasn't too far off as an analogy...<P><B>You state "Let me go over the philosophy of 'inspection'. The first thing to keep in mind is that nobody is actually inspecting you, at least not in the way that the word would indicate. They are looking at you closely, not turning your clothing inside out to see the labels.<P>Inspection does not show your britches.<P>What it does show are the things that the game engine doesn't show. If your character is wearing a cloak the only way to know it is to 'inspect' them. The game engine isn't showing what would otherwise be obvious. Inspection only shows the name of an item and it's type (and only that by the icon that shows in inventory). Inspection does not reveal what is in a bag, stats on any item, or what color underwear your character has on. It only shows enough information to allow other players to know what your character would actually look like if the game engine could show every item you are wearing.<P>There is nothing invasive about inspecting someone."<P>From my perspective, if inspection just showed the graphical icon, and didn't contain the item name, THAT would be what a person would see in RL if they inspected you, NOT the labels. That should be a simple fix to the inspect complaint. It would then be up to the person inspecting to make assumption about what brand of clothing you are wearing. </B> <P>And I would agree with you, if only those icons that you refer to were representative of what the character would see.  I would think that, for example, a powerful scimitar would be obviously different than a rusty one.  But, again due to limitations of the game, they use the same icon in inventory.  The fact that a character <I>should</I> be able to see the flames on the blade is not reflected in the inventory icon.  And it's certainly something that someone would see.<P><B>For example they might ask themselves: "Is that Tizmak or Ulthork armor?  Hmm. .I don't know, they are too similar to tell by looking at them.  Are those Kromriff Military leggings?  Maybe I'll ask they person."  <BR>Similarly you might in RL think :"Is that a Rolex watch hes wearing? Or just a knockoff? Maybe I'll ask the person"</B><P>Fair enough.  I can't argue with that.  But the cases where a character would be experienced enough to know to ask that question in the first place (because, I would assume, he's seen both types of armor) might also be able to tell what it was by looking at it.  Nobody is making knockoff Ulthork in Norrath, but I can see your point when you use the Rolex example.  But a lot of people could tell a Casio from a Rolex at a glance.  In Norrath without inspect, you can't.<P><B>Any more information that you can gather from inspection IS invasive.  I wear white dress shirts in RL.  The only way a person knows what brand they are is if they ask, or turn my label.  Turning my label is invasive.  At least if they ask, I have the option of letting them know.<P>With the current way inspection works, the person would 'know' if the watcht was a knockoff or real. Or what brand my shirt is... that doesn't fit your description of the philosophy of inspection.</B><P>Well, some people might be able to recognize the brand if they were a shirt expert.  But we're not talking about telling one brand of basic white shirt from another, we're talking about telling snakeskin boots from leather boots.  There aren't 20 different makers of Tizmak armor out there, and people aren't peering to see the label.  They are looking at differences that should be very obvious if we had a unique texture for every item.<P><B>You claim that this is a group game, then why do you take away from character interaction by allowing inspections without the person being inspecteds permission?</B><P>Well, this one hits in the right spot.  But then again I hear enough people telling me that once they get inspected they get begged and that annoys them.  That's also interaction...  And how much more annoying would it be if they had to ask for details on your stuff before begging.<P>Honestly I get just as annoyed with people asking to inspect me as I suspect other people do by being inspected.  To me inspecting is just looking at me, and I'd rather not have to give permission to other to do so.<P><B>Now, here are my questions to you.  Why NOT make it so the character can turn off what is veiwable (i.e. labels)?  Would that be offensive to you because you could no longer see what we were wearing? If you answer yes to the second question you should ask yourself why.<P>Hopefully I made my point.  If not, oh well, the game goes on.</B><P>As I said, I rarely inspect people.  I'm not overawed by equipment, so I really don't care much.<P>And I've given the reasons for inspection.  It allows players an easy way to overcome the limitations of the game.<P><B>Just my 2cp worth.<P>Aleator Level 51.4 Wood Elf Druid/Tradesman <BR>Keepers of the Sliph<BR>Grand Master Alcoholic (200)<BR>Master Blacksmith (187)<BR>Master Fletcher (163)<BR>Master Brewer (150)<BR>Master Baker (137)<BR>Master Potter (122)<BR>Master Tailor(102)<BR>Etc.<P>Aggogg Meadhogg Level 47 Troll Warrior <P>Scelestus Swiifttaiil Level 36 Iksar Monky</B><P>... with comments from Alan    <IMG SRC="http://boards.station.sony.com/ubb/everquest/smile.gif"><BR>

<hr>

Tilin_Bladejack wrote:<P><B>It seems the majority of players that I have encountered, as well as the ones who's concerns you have responded to in this thread, disagree with you on the invasiveness of inspection.<P>At what point does the voice of the player community outweigh that of the the designers and staff? It seems pretty clear that the majority of us want some means of restricting the amount of detail provided by inspection, as opposed to just not being told it has happenned.</B><P>Actually, the response has been mixed.  I haven't counted the 'yes' and 'no' responses, but I'd guess that the 142 responses would break up pretty evenly.  I haven't been posting a bunch of the comments from people that agree with the way it is now, probably because I didn't feel a need to convince them of anything.   <IMG SRC="http://boards.station.sony.com/ubb/everquest/smile.gif">  I'll post a few now, just so that both sides can be represented.<P>But, again, I can easily sense that most debate over this issue involves emotion as the primary motivator on either side.  With the emotional response rather split, sticking with the logical one (which I have yet to be convinced isn't logical) is the way to go.<P><BR><B>you know if peopel inspecting you bugs you a solution is to make a emote for it.  inspection doesn't realyl bother me but i have an emote for it just for laughs.  the one i use is,<BR>/emote adjusts his "equipment"...<P>but i've seen others like<BR>/emote 's equipmet looks back at you<BR>or things like that<BR>falkahnhan righteousfire</B><P>And...<P><BR>pumkin54 wrote:<P><BR><B>The whole uproar about inspection seems plain silly to me.  I regularly inspect people and I regularly get inspected.  Who cares?  When people look at me, I think "Yep, check out my cool new staff!  *strut strut*'  I like checking out other people because it tells me if I should maybe be looking for an upgrade in my armor.  I'm a lvl 14 druid and I recently inspected a lvl 41 so I could know what to look forward to in the future.  It's not an invasive anything.  It just seems like people have to have *something* to complain about, so here it is.  Of course, you're welcome to disagree with me.  I'm just sharing my opinion!   <IMG SRC="http://boards.station.sony.com/ubb/everquest/tongue.gif"></B><P>Also...<P><BR><B>I personally LIKE it when people inspect me...inspecting always follows with 'WOW your equipment is so awesome' and things like that. Maybe I would think differently if my equipment sucked...but it doesnt  <IMG SRC="http://boards.station.sony.com/ubb/everquest/wink.gif"> I actually think its kinda fun walkin up to the Tunnel in east commons where a lot of people are and have like, 5 people inspect me at once...then they all say how awesome I am etc. etc. etc. Me? Brag? Never  <IMG SRC="http://boards.station.sony.com/ubb/everquest/wink.gif"><P>-Nanaki Ikanan<BR>56 Myrmidon<BR>Druzzil-Ro</B><P>And more like it.<P>Like I said, the discussion seems split fairly evenly along emotional lines.<P>The logical point is that the game engine can't show all your stuff.  Inspecting someone is only displaying the information that you would be able to see in a perfect game engine.  No stats are displayed.  People can't see into bags.  It reveals the information that should be visible by, at most, peering closely at the character.<P><BR>NexToneX wrote:<P><B>Why not just change the word from inspecting, to looking.<P>Anoobie is looking at you.<P>then it doesn't feel like someone is going through my pockets.</B><P>That might be a good idea.  Perhaps a way to lessen the emotional impact of inspection.  It might, however, be far too late for a change like this to have much affect.<P><BR>Milvang wrote:<P><B>The level of detail that it is currently possibly to display on character models make it nescesary to have some king of inspection mechanism. Even if you could do muck more deatiled models, then a 2d image on a screen will never come close to a full size live model.<P>I see two major problems with the current inspection system.<P>First the inspection message. The way it is worded makes the action seem more invasive than the game technicality that I think is is. Something along the lines of "Soandso is looking at you", would be much better, and lead to far less conflict. I mean 'inspecting' is invasive, 'looking at' is perfectly acceptable in most cultures. The fact that there is a message at all, suggest that the action has meaning in the game world, and iis not only a part of the user interface, which I think it should ideally be.<P>The 2nd problem is that inspecting actually reveals too much information. The names of items should not be readily available on inspection. The problem is that there is no skill (player or character) involved in determining what item you are looking at. As with the example of the wrist watch someone was wearing, then to some people it with just be a wrist watch, some people might see it was a Rolex, and the trained eye might even be able to tell if it was fake (just from looking). If it was possible each item should have a somewhat more detailed picture than the inventory icon, and that is what should pop up with you click on the item in someones inventory, rather than the name. Unfortunatly I am sure that would take up a lot of space, not to mention resources actually making the pictures.<P>I personally think I would introduce 2 types of inspection. One that did not give a message, and only showed the icons with no possibility of getting the name. And a 2nd option that gave a message, had a delay, or required acceptence from the inspectee, that gave the names as you get it now.</B><P>It might be possible to do something like replacing the name of the item with an appropriate description.  So if you were to inspect Aradune and right-click on his flaming sword, rather than having it read Fiery Avenger, it might read "A sword with flames writhing up the blade" or something like that.<P>And that would be a better solution.  But...<P>As usual, such a thing would take a lot of time to do.  We'd have to write up descriptions for every single item or item type (Maybe one description for all magical leather types) and add them to the game.  That would be a tremendous task.  We'd also have to add that information to each item.  I don't even know if that could be done (I don't know all the ins and outs of item data structures).<P>I'll propose it, just to see what the team thinks.  But, honestly, I can't picture using resources to add this that could be used for something else.  In the end, though, it's up to the team to decide that.<P>Alan<BR>

<hr>

Tagadin wrote:<P><B>I've been following the thread on inspection and I would like to ask a question. Is there a way to turn off the message that you recieve when someone is inspecting you? In a previous post you said... <P>"There really is no need to remove it, we just went for the more flexible idea, allow players to choose to turn it off if they wish."<P>I may have read it wrong, but it kinda implied that we had the power to turn the message off if people were annoying us with it. Personally, I couldn't care less if people are peeking at my undies or measure my feet for new sneakers. I just get tired of seeing the "Soinso is inspecting you" message...</B><P>Sure, you can do it from the command line in game.  Here are the instructions from the supplemental manual in your EverQuest directory (actually, it's from the one we're updating now...)<P>/inspect [ON/OFF]  Toggles on and off the message that you see when someone is inspecting you.<P>Alan<BR>

<hr>

Axiss wrote:<P><B>Slight problem with that.  In-game, the "/inspect off" command disables the ability of you being able to right-click on a person and view what they are inspecting.<P>It's a pretty common command on the pvp servers such as Rallos.  It's used by people who want the ability to "con" fellow players, and not inspect them as most people who run up to you and inspect blatantly are PK'ers who are seeking people with "phat lewts"<P>Not sure if the /inspect command was meant to toggle the ability of a person to inspect another by right-clicking, but I have yet to find a way to disable the message you receive when you are being inspected by another player.</B><P>Yup, I was wrong.  Good thing I posted that or the updated supplemental manual would have been wrong too.<P>The /inspect toggle is indeed for turning off your ability to inspect others with a right-click of your mouse.  Mostly useful for those that use their mouse for movement (though it seems that the PvP players have adapted, as is to be expected).<P>To turn off the inspect message, you need to edit your Eqclient.ini file.  Just open it up and change the line:<P>ShowInspectMessage=TRUE<P>To read:<P>ShowInspectMessage=FALSE<P>Sorry for the confusion.<P>Alan<BR>

<hr>

<BR>Kiriani_Greywynd wrote:<P><B>since yer updating the manual...<P>the manual has the command /shownames listedforturning off the names over hour heads...<P>needless to say it doesn't work</B><P>You are correct, it doesn't work...  Right now I'm not sure why.  We'll make sure it either works or is taken off the list by the time we're done with the manual.  Thanks.<P><BR>Milvang wrote:<P><B>I noticed you have changed the message to<P>"Soandso is looking at your equipment"<P>Great wording, and great job.</B><P>We did?  Cool.   <IMG SRC="http://boards.station.sony.com/ubb/everquest/smile.gif"><P>I can't keep up with all this stuff...<P>Alan<P><BR>






